g.text: Try QVD today to see how you can simplify
the majority of desktop management and
access requirements that you face today.
Remote Access
...but it also means that you have greater control over data and applications without needing
access to the devices that are using your infrastructure.
Not only does this mean that your users are able to work as safely and seamlessly as if they
are in the office...
QVD provides strong security to ensure that communications are encrypted and is capable of
working in extremely low-bandwidth environments.
With the QVD client installed on any laptop or mobile device, your road-warriors and executives
can access their desktops from anywhere on the Internet.
Keep your laptops and mobile devices clean with QVD.
You also don't need to worry about tricky VPN configurations.
You don't need to install business critical applications on systems that are outside of your
network with QVD.
Built-in Security
and you can be secure in the knowledge that your data stays in the data center where it
belongs.
Since desktop images remain read-only, your virtual desktops are automatically protected from
malicious rootkit style attacks, keeping your network virus free...
QVD provides a secure framework for your users to access their desktops.
All connections to virtual desktops are protected using certificate-based encryption, so that
user authentication and desktop interaction takes place securely.
Desktop Operations Management
Logs are also stored separately from the disk image used by the virtual machine, allowing staff
to review log data retrospectively to gain further insight into any issues that a user may be
experiencing.
These facilities allow support staff direct access to the virtual machine that a user is
accessing at any point in time.
Adding VNC or SSH support to Virtual Machines is a basic operation.
Each Virtual Machine supports direct console access either via a terminal or through the
applet provided in the Web Administration Panel.
Virtual Desktop Image Management
Image Versioning, Rollout and Rollback
User data remains unaffected during the operation.
so that updates can be rolled out in stages to limit corporate-wide impact and reduce support
overhead.
As a result, rollback to a previous desktop image is as simple as selecting the image version
to rollback to and clicking on a button to effect the change.
Disk Images can be tagged with version numbers
For more advanced administration there is a fully scriptable Command Line Utility
...allowing you to automate many of your Image Management tasks to suit your own
procedures.
Web-based Administration
Assigning disk images to users is a simple point and click operation.
...making it simple to load and update disk images so that they are ready to use.
For administrators who are not confident working on the command-line, QVD includes a
Web-based Administration Panel...
QVD uses open source tools
By creating or updating a single desktop image, you can service hundreds of users in an
instant.
This means that you are able to create or update an image from any system that has the
correct software installed.
to create and update desktop images
...and minimizes the amount of work required to keep all users up to date and in sync.
This helps to reduce the amount of disk space required to support many users...
A Desktop Image defines the software and desktop environment that will be presented to a
group of users.
Automated Desktop Provisioning
Integrated authentication services
By using one of the provided plugins, you can continue to make use of your existing
authentication resources to start provisioning virtual desktops to your users from.
Thanks to QVD's programmable nature, plugins are available to use external authentication
systems such as Active Directory or any other LDAP repository to handle user provisioning and
authentication.
You don't have to store your users in QVD.
This is called Automated Desktop Provisioning
...so that your administrative tasks are reduced to simply adding the new user to the system.
QVD automatically creates a virtual machine for the user and loads the appropriate desktop
image into the virtual machine
...and is handled by QVD based on the desktop images that you have added to the system for
each different set of users.
Whenever a new user joins your organization, you have the problem of setting up and
configuring a workstation to meet that user's requirements.
QVD makes this very easy.
...are instantly taken care of.
and all of the network resources that should be available...
all security policies that apply to that user...
All of the software that the user needs access to...
As soon as the user logs into a workstation using the provided username and password, a
new virtual desktop environment will be created.
Simply add the user to the QVD environment and set a password.
can be a real headache.
But you could make it easier by virtualizing all of your desktops
using QVD.
